Finally, Gunell et¬†al. (2007) considered the case of Venus. The greater mass of Venus than Mars causes exospheric densities to fall faster with altitude at Venus than Mars. Consequently, the halo of soft X-rays emitted by charge exchange surrounding Venus has a narrower radial extent (and is therefore more difficult to observe) than that at Mars, as shown in Fig.¬†33. Fig.¬†33
