CCDs are large format silicon detectors where the charge generated by an absorbed X-ray is localized within the silicon by fields induced by the gate array structure. After an accumulation time, which is short enough that most pixels contain no events and no pixels contain more than a single event, the charge is transferred across the detector to a readout array by manipulating the voltages on the gate array. Front-side illuminated CCDs have relatively low efficiency at lower energies as the X-ray must pass through the metallic gate array structure. Back-side illuminated devices, however, offer high quantum efficiency in the soft X-ray band (Fig.¬†54). CCDs also provide moderate energy resolution: FWHM‚àº50eV\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
