X-rays from the magnetosheath are not the only ones that will be observed by a soft X-ray instrument. The cosmic X-ray background, both the diffuse component shown in Fig.¬†28 and the contribution from point sources shown in Fig.¬†30 will also be observed. Both were well measured by RASS at the energies of interest. Since the spectrum of the cosmic X-ray background is of great scientific interest, it is well known and conversion from ROSAT count rates to a particular instrument is trivial. It should be noted that the bulk of the heliospheric solar wind charge emission has not been removed from the ROSAT maps, so the typical contribution of the heliospheric SWCX to background is included. The near-Earth environment also emits strong line emissions in the far and extreme UV which can contaminate the X-ray band. We have used the neutral distribution from Hodges (1973) to calculate the LyŒ±\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
